<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a sharp retreat from Wall Street, Barclays plans to shrink its investment banking business by cutting more than a quarter of the operation&#8217;s work force, <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/08/barclays-to-cut-7000-jobs-in-investment-bank-create-internal-bad-bank/?module=BlogPost-Title&#038;version=Blog%20Main&#038;contentCollection=Investment%20Banking&#038;action=Click&#038;pgtype=Blogs&#038;region=Body" title="The DealBook article.">Chad Bray and Jenny Anderson write in DealBook</a>. Antony P. Jenkins, the bank&#8217;s chief executive, is aiming to reshape the bank and revive its image after a series of scandals.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A number of weaker businesses â including the trading of physical commodities outside of precious metals and some branch networks outside of Britain â will be placed in an internal âbad bankâ where they will be sold or run off. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">THE RISE OF JACK MA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> âThe first time Jack Ma used the Internet, in 1995, he searched for âbeerâ and âChinaâ but found no results,â <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/08/technology/the-unlikely-ascent-of-jack-ma-alibabas-founder.html?_r=0">Neil Gough and Alexandra Stevenson write in The New York Times</a></b>. Such began the ascent of Mr. Ma, who started the Alibaba Group in 1999, a rise that is âremarkable for not following the traditional script,â they write.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;<b>Unlike Facebookâs Mark Zuckerberg</b>, Appleâs Steven P. Jobs or Microsoftâs Bill Gates, Mr. Ma, 49, has no background in computing and professes not to understand technology,â they write. His role at Alibaba has always been as the companyâs main strategist, they add, âa flamboyant motivator in chief to his staff and a relentless opponent to those who have competed against him.â A former English teacher, he has also proved to be a serial disrupter with a knack for reimagining old industries like retailing and finance. âI had always wished that I was born in a period of war. I could have been a general,â Mr. Ma once said of his youth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Now, Alibaba is Chinaâs largest online retailer</b>, and Mr. Ma, who own 8.9 percent of the company, is poised to join the highest ranks of technology industry titans. A look at Alibabaâs I.P.O. filing suggests that <b>the company is also planning to get bigger</b>. Alibaba has made waves for its deals in the United States, but, according to its prospectus, it remains focused on investing in China, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/07/alibabas-acquisition-strategy-focused-largely-on-china-and-mobile">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced writes</a></b>. The document also highlights the progress the company has already made in mobile.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> REVERSE MORTGAGE GAMBLE <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> With more homeowners set to reach retirement age in the coming years, some private investors are betting on a revival of reverse mortgages, an investment product aimed at older people in need of cash, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/07/some-investors-bet-on-return-to-reverse-mortgages/?">DealBookâs Matthew Goldstein writes</a></b>. One reverse mortgage start-up based in New Jersey has raised about $230 million in a private offering. Investors in the private sale of shares included hedge funds, wealthy individual investors and customers of the investment firm.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The private placement in February</b> could lead to an initial public offering of the company, which operates under the name Reverse Mortgage Funding. A public offering would make Reverse Mortgage Funding one of the first stand-alone publicly traded companies that specialize in reverse mortgages, which provide government-guaranteed loans to homeowners based on the equity value in their homes in exchange for fees and interest payments that are paid when the loan comes due, Mr. Goldstein writes. Perhaps more important, a successful debut on the public markets could <b>encourage other players in the space</b> to hold public offerings of their own.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Weekly <b>jobless claims</b> are out at 8:30 a.m. <b>Charles I. Plosser</b>, president of the Philadelphia Fed, gives a speech on monetary policy in New York at 8 a.m. <b>Daniel K. Tarullo</b>, a Federal Reserve governor, gives a speech at the Chicago Fedâs banking conference at 8:30 a.m. <b>James B. Bullard</b>, president of the St. Louis Fed, speaks at a household finance conference. <b>Ken Moelis</b>, the founder and chief executive of Moelis &#038; Company, is on Fox Business Network at 9 a.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: <b>Janet L. Yellen</b>, chairwoman of the Federal Reserve, testifies before the Senate Budget Committee on the economic and fiscal outlook at 9:30 a.m. The <b>House Committee on Financial Services</b> holds a hearing at 10 a.m. entitled âThe Annual Testimony of the Secretary of the Treasury on the State of the International Financial System.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">GROWING PAINS FOR A GOLDMAN SACHS FUND <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> One of Goldman Sachsâs most notable investment vehicles, Petershill, has been less than extraordinary, âeffectively saved by one good bet among a number of duds,â<b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/07/growing-pains-for-a-goldman-sachs-fund"> Rachel Abrams writes in DealBook</a></b>. Now, as a second version of the fund, which buys stakes in big-name hedge funds, seeks to raise money, <b>investors appear to be holding back</b>. For its part, Goldman says it is satisfied with the pace of fund-raising.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Goldman so far has raised more than $200 million</b> for Petershill II, which has a goal of $1 billion since it went to market last fall. Goldman says the fund has also raised an additional $190 million to date from offshore investors. By comparison, the original Petershill, started in 2007 when capital markets were exuberant, reached its $1 billion goal in several months. Petershill II is being managed and marketed by Goldmanâs asset management group, which is poised to take on a bigger role in generating revenue for Goldman as other lines of business, like trading in bonds and stocks, have become less profitable, Ms. Abrams writes.</p>
</div>
